'''Mountains of Slovenia''' are part of the [[Alps]] and of the [[Dinaric Alps|Dinarides]].
==Alps== The Alps in Slovenia can be divided into:
*[[Julian Alps]] ({{lang-sl|Julijske Alpe}}) in the northwestern part of Slovenia. The highest peak is Mount [[Triglav]] - 2,864 metres (9,396 feet) above sea.<ref name="hribi">http://www.hribi.net/seznamgora.asp?lng=1 Mountains of Slovenia - Hribi.net</ref> *[[Karawanks]] ({{lang-sl|Karavanke}})- a massive ridge that forms a natural boundary between Slovenia and [[Austria]]. The highest peak is Mt. [[Stol (Karawanks)|Stol]] - 2,236 m ((7,336 feet).<ref name="hribi"/> *[[Kamnik–Savinja Alps]] ({{lang-sl|Kamniško-Savinjske Alpe}}) lie to the south of [[Karawanks]]. The highest peak is Mt. [[Grintovec]] - 2,558 m (8,392 feet) above sea.<ref name="hribi"/>
==Dinarides== In the [[Inner Carniola]], the highest peaks are Veliki Snežnik ({{convert|1796|m}}, part of the [[Snežnik|Snežnik plateau]] and the highest non-[[Alps|Alpine]] peak in Slovenia, and Suhi vrh ({{convert|1313|m}}), part of the [[Nanos (plateau)|Nanos plateau]]. They're both part of the [[Dinaric Alps]], a mountain chain that spans towards the southeast. The highest peak is [[Snežnik (mountain)|Snežnik]].
Part of the Dinaric Alps are also the [[Gorjanci]] mountain range, and in the [[Slovenian Istria]], Mt. [[Slavnik]] (1,028 m) and Mt. [[Vremščica]] (1,027 m).
==List of notable peaks== This list contains height (above sea level) of some notable peaks in [[Slovenia]].
